<article title='Outline_of_critical_theory'><paragraph>The following<space/><link><target>Outline (list)</target><part>outline</part></link><space/>is provided as an overview of and topical guide to critical theory:</paragraph><paragraph><bold><link><target>Critical theory</target></link></bold><space/>&amp;ndash; examination and critique of society and culture, drawing from knowledge across the social sciences and humanities. The term has two different meanings with different origins and histories: one originating in sociology and the other in literary criticism. This has led to the very literal use of 'critical theory' as an umbrella term to describe any theory founded upon critique.</paragraph><paragraph><template><target>TOC limit</target><arg name="limit">2</arg></template></paragraph><heading level='2'>Essence of critical theory</heading><list type='bullet'><listitem><link><target>Cultural studies</target></link><space/>&amp;ndash;</listitem><listitem><link><target>List of critical theorists</target><part>Critical theorists</part></link><space/>&amp;ndash;</listitem><listitem><link><target>List of works in critical theory</target><part>Works in critical theory</part></link><space/>&amp;ndash;</listitem><listitem><link><target>Truth theory</target></link><space/>&amp;ndash;</listitem></list><heading level='2'>Branches of critical theory</heading><list type='bullet'><listitem><link><target>Social theory</target></link><space/>&amp;ndash;</listitem><listitem><link><target>Literary theory</target></link><space/>&amp;ndash;</listitem><listitem><link><target>Thing theory</target></link><space/>&amp;ndash;</listitem><listitem><link><target>Andrew Feenberg</target><part>Critical theory of technology</part></link><space/>&amp;ndash;</listitem><listitem><link><target>Critical legal studies</target></link><space/>&amp;ndash;</listitem></list><heading level='2'>Gender studies</heading><paragraph><template><target>main</target><arg>Gender studies</arg></template></paragrap